rld War II in youth organizations such as Camp Fire Girls, Girl Scouts, YWCA Y-Teens, schools, and even magazines like Seventeen. She shows the particular ways that girls’ identities and roles were configured, and reveals the links between internationalist youth culture, mainstream U.S. educational goals, and the U.S. government in creating and marketing that internationalist girl, thus shaping the girls’ sense of responsibilities as citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCitizenshipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGirlszUnited StatesxSocieties and clubsxHistoryy20th century. 0aInternationalismxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aResponsibilityxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTeenage girlsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agirls, cold war, war, global, responsibility, history, United States, citizens, girlhood, girl, nation, nationhood, gender, military, WW2, world war 2, youth culture, internationalist, internationalist girl, postwar, postwar U.S., postwar united states, us history, women's history, women's studies, childhood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357582740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813575827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813575827.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  a